{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626697"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:41:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:41:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17092"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17092"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.5,0.1,0.3,0.05,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9782"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76850"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9782","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9782"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17092"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62355"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5115"},{"type":"tags","id":"7005"},{"type":"tags","id":"10203"},{"type":"tags","id":"10214"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22960"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23050"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76850","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76850"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman has blood tests as part of a routine health check. Her serum calcium is 2.8 mmol/L (2.1-2.6). This triggers the release of calcitonin from the thyroid gland.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes calcitonin\u0027s primary physiological effect?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreases osteoclast activity","Increasing intestinal calcium absorption","Stimulates osteoblast activity","Enhances renal calcium reabsorption","Promotes vitamin D activation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECalcitonin\u0027s primary action is to \u003Cstrong\u003Edecrease osteoclast activity\u003C/strong\u003E, thereby reducing bone resorption and lowering serum calcium levels. This hormone is released from thyroid C cells in response to hypercalcaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent actions of other calcium-regulating hormones:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing intestinal calcium absorption\u003C/strong\u003E is a key action of vitamin D (specifically calcitriol), which is important in conditions like osteomalacia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulating osteoblast activity\u003C/strong\u003E is more associated with parathyroid hormone\u0027s anabolic effects when given intermittently, as used in some osteoporosis treatments\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhancing renal calcium reabsorption\u003C/strong\u003E is an action of parathyroid hormone, which is crucial in preventing hypocalcaemia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPromoting vitamin D activation\u003C/strong\u003E occurs via parathyroid hormone stimulating 1-alpha-hydroxylase in the kidneys\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EClinically, synthetic calcitonin has limited therapeutic use but may be prescribed for acute severe hypercalcaemia, Paget\u0027s disease of bone, or osteoporosis, where its osteoclast-inhibiting properties are beneficial.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Calcitonin is produced by thyroid C cells of the thyroid gland in response to elevated blood calcium levels.","Calcitonin reduces blood calcium by inhibiting osteoclast activity and increasing calcium excretion by the kidney"],"references":["Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","McLaughlin MB, Awosika AO, Jialal I. Calcitonin. [Updated 2023 Aug 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537269/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62355"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17092"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62355","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62355"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T14:11:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T14:12:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9782"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76850"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":n